I still remember struggling with hypothesis testing at the start.

I knew the formulas. I could calculate z and t values.

But if someone asked which test to use and why, I would pause.

That changed when I stopped treating it like a formula topic and started seeing it as a simple decision process.

This cheat sheet captures that flow really well.

This is how I now think about it:

→ Start with a question, not a formula
Are you comparing means, checking relationships, or testing assumptions?

→ Define H₀ and H₁ clearly
If this step is weak, everything after it becomes confusing

→ Pick the test based on data, not preference
-Known variance, large sample → z-test
-Unknown variance → t-test
-Two categorical variables → chi-square
-More than two groups → ANOVA

→ Then comes calculation (this is the easy part)

→ Final step is interpretation

p-value is just a signal. You still need to explain what it means in context

One thing I learned the hard way:

Most errors don’t come from calculations

They come from:
-wrong test selection
-ignoring assumptions
-misreading p-values

When I started working on real datasets and ML experiments, this became very practical:
-Comparing two models → t-test
-Checking if a feature is useful → chi-square
-Running A/B tests → same concepts, just applied differently

If you’re learning this right now, don’t rush to formulas.

Take a few problems.

Ask yourself: “What exactly am I trying to prove here?”

That question alone clears up half the confusion.

If this helped, save it for later and repost so others don’t struggle the way we did.



















